{"questionId":"9075097","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>An electrical circuit is used during an experiment to measure the current <em>I</em> in a variable&nbsp;resistor of resistance <em>R</em>. The emf of the cell is e and the cell has an internal resistance <em>r</em>.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/5b12fa9c14731d8426295d7d8ecee912b4546745.png\"></p>\n<p>A graph shows the variation of <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{1}{I}\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mn>1</mn>\n    <mi>I</mi>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span> with <em>R</em>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/ec90d9a8f13d70a1559d4fac7127d5cb8b405318.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Show that the gradient of the graph is equal to <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{1}{e}\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mn>1</mn>\n    <mi>e</mi>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>«<em>ε</em> = <em>IR + Ir</em>»</p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{1}{I} = \\frac{R}{\\varepsilon } + \\frac{r}{\\varepsilon }\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mn>1</mn>\n    <mi>I</mi>\n  </mfrac>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mfrac>\n    <mi>R</mi>\n    <mi>ε</mi>\n  </mfrac>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mfrac>\n    <mi>r</mi>\n    <mi>ε</mi>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span></p>\n<p>identifies equation with <em>y</em> = <em>mx + c</em></p>\n<p><em>«</em>hence <em>m</em> =&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{1}{\\varepsilon }\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mn>1</mn>\n    <mi>ε</mi>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span><em>»</em></p>\n<p><em>No mark for stating data booklet equation</em></p>\n<p><em>Do not accept working where r is ignored or ε = IR is used</em></p>\n<p><em>OWTTE</em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"9075097","referenceCode":"17N.3.SL.TZ0.2a","subjectId":"46-dp-physics-last-assessment-2024","title":"Show that the gradient of the graph is equal to 1 e .","paper":"3","level":"SL","questionNumber":"a","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Core","Core","Topic 5: Electricity and magnetism","5.3 – Electric cells","Core","Topic 5: Electricity and magnetism"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}